# GitHub Repository Setup Guide

## Step 1: Create Repository Structure

Create the following folder structure locally:

```
pcb-defect-detection/
├── src/
│   ├── __init__.py
│   ├── dataset.py
│   ├── model.py
│   ├── train.py
│   └── inference.py
├── config/
│   └── config.yaml (optional)
├── notebooks/
│   └── exploration.ipynb (optional)
├── .gitignore
├── requirements.txt
├── README.md
└── LICENSE
```

## Step 2: Initialize Git Repository

Open terminal in the project root directory and run:

```bash
# Initialize git repository
git init

# Add all files
git add .

# Make first commit
git commit -m "Initial commit: PCB defect detection project"
```

## Step 3: Create GitHub Repository

1. Go to [GitHub](https://github.com)
2. Click the "+" icon → "New repository"
3. Repository name: `pcb-defect-detection`
4. Description: "Automated PCB defect detection using Faster R-CNN and PyTorch Lightning"
5. Choose Public or Private
6. **Do NOT** initialize with README (you already have one)
7. Click "Create repository"

## Step 4: Connect Local to Remote

```bash
# Add remote origin (replace YOUR_USERNAME)
git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/pcb-defect-detection.git

# Push to GitHub
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
```

## Step 5: Add Topics and Description

On your GitHub repository page:
1. Click "About" settings (gear icon)
2. Add topics: `deep-learning`, `object-detection`, `pytorch`, `pytorch-lightning`, `computer-vision`, `pcb-inspection`, `faster-rcnn`
3. Add website (if you have one)
4. Save changes

## Step 6: Create Additional Files (Optional)

### LICENSE
If you want to add a license:
1. Click "Add file" → "Create new file"
2. Name it `LICENSE`
3. Click "Choose a license template"
4. Select MIT License (or your preference)
5. Commit

### GitHub Actions (Optional CI/CD)
Create `.github/workflows/python-app.yml` for automated testing:

```yaml
name: Python application

on: [push, pull_request]

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
    - uses: actions/checkout@v3
    - name: Set up Python
      uses: actions/setup-python@v4
      with:
        python-version: '3.10'
    - name: Install dependencies
      run: |
        python -m pip install --upgrade pip
        pip install -r requirements.txt
    - name: Lint with flake8
      run: |
        pip install flake8
        flake8 . --count --select=E9,F63,F7,F82 --show-source --statistics
```

## Step 7: Update README with Your Information

Edit README.md to include:
- Your name and contact
- Link to your repository
- Results from your training runs
- Sample detection images
- Any specific setup instructions for your dataset

## Step 8: Best Practices

### Branching Strategy
```bash
# Create development branch
git checkout -b develop

# Create feature branches
git checkout -b feature/new-augmentation

# Merge back to main when ready
git checkout main
git merge develop
```

### Commit Messages
Use clear, descriptive commit messages:
```bash
git commit -m "Add: CoarseDropout augmentation for better generalization"
git commit -m "Fix: Box validation in SubsetWithTransform"
git commit -m "Improve: Reduce anchor sizes for small defects"
```

### Tags for Releases
```bash
# Tag important versions
git tag -a v1.0.0 -m "First stable release"
git push origin v1.0.0
```

## Step 9: Share Your Work

Add badges to README.md:

```markdown
![Python](https://img.shields.io/badge/python-3.8+-blue.svg)
![PyTorch](https://img.shields.io/badge/pytorch-2.0+-red.svg)
![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-MIT-green.svg)
```

## Step 10: Maintain Your Repository

Regular maintenance:
- Respond to issues
- Review pull requests
- Update dependencies
- Add documentation
- Share results and visualizations

## Common Git Commands Reference

```bash
# Check status
git status

# Add specific files
git add src/model.py

# Commit with message
git commit -m "Your message"

# Push changes
git push origin main

# Pull latest changes
git pull origin main

# View commit history
git log --oneline

# Undo last commit (keep changes)
git reset --soft HEAD~1

# Discard local changes
git checkout -- filename.py
```

## Troubleshooting

### Large files error
If you accidentally committed large files:
```bash
# Remove from git but keep locally
git rm --cached large_file.ckpt

# Add to .gitignore
echo "*.ckpt" >> .gitignore

# Commit the changes
git commit -m "Remove large checkpoint files"
```

### Authentication
Use Personal Access Token instead of password:
1. GitHub → Settings → Developer settings → Personal access tokens
2. Generate new token with repo access
3. Use token as password when pushing

Or set up SSH keys for easier authentication.
